[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is Ladybird, a truly independent web browser built from scratch, not a fork of anything. 62,900 GitHub stars, BSD-2 licensed, backed by a 501c3 nonprofit with eight full-time engineers, and platinum sponsors that'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'include Futo, Shopify, and Cloudflare. Its own rendering engine called LibWeb, its own JavaScript engine called LibJS, its own Web Assembly engine, no Chromium, no WebKit, no Gecko. This is'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the first genuinely new browser engine to seriously target web standards in over 20 years. Currently pre-alpha with the first developer alpha targeting Linux and macOS in 2026.'

[00:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'If you\'ve been watching the web slowly collapse into a Chromium monoculture and wondering whether anyone was going to do anything about it, Ladybird is the answer that has already shipped enough code to take seriously. Ladybird is a complete web browser implementation with'

[00:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'its own engine for every layer of the stack. The rendering pipeline is LibWeb, written in C++ and increasingly in Rust as the project transitions toward memory-safe languages for security-critical components.'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'JavaScript runs through LibJS, Web Assembly runs through LibWasm. Network requests, image decoding, cryptography, and inter-process communication all live in their own libraries.'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The whole thing started as a subproject inside SerenityOS, Andreas Kling\'s hobby operating system, before spinning out into its own organization in 2024. The code base is genuinely independent. There is no shared lineage with'

[01:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Chromium\'s Blink, with Apple\'s WebKit, or with Mozilla\'s Gecko. When the team says built from scratch, they mean it in the literal sense with provable Git history going back to the original 2018 commits. The metrics tell a story that'

[01:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is genuinely unusual for a project this ambitious. 62,900 GitHub stars, which is in the same league as established frameworks rather than what you would expect for a pre-alpha browser. 3,000 forks, BSD-2 licensed, which is the most permissive'

[01:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'license a browser project could realistically choose. Anyone can fork it, embed it, build a commercial product on top of it with no copyleft strings attached. The Ladybird Browser Initiative is a registered'

[02:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '501(c)(3) non-profit, which means donations are tax-deductible and the organization is legally required to spend its funds on the mission rather than returning value to shareholders. Eight full-time paid engineers with'

[02:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'additional volunteer contributors merging meaningful work every week. Platinum sponsors are Futo, Shopify, and Cloudflare. Lower-tier sponsors run from gold all the way to copper, plus thousands of individual donations. Zero'

[02:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'search engine deals, zero data collection, zero advertising revenue. The technical architecture is the part that makes Ladybird genuinely interesting. The browser uses a proper multi-process'

[02:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'design. Separate processes for rendering, image decoding, and network requests, sandboxed from each other for security. The rendering engine implements web standards directly from the'

[02:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'specifications, which is a refreshingly different starting point than the reverse engineering of existing engines approach that most browser forks take. Memory-safety critical components are being progressively rewritten in Swift'

[03:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and Rust. The whole codebase is auditable, single organization, and free of the legacy assumptions that have accumulated in Chromium and WebKit over two decades of patches. There is no telemetry, no phone home, no ad blocker'

[03:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rebellion because there is no ad business to defend. And critically, no conflict of interest between the browser team and a parent corporation that needs to monetize you. Building Ladybird from source is'

[03:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'genuinely accessible if you have a modern Linux box or a Mac with Xcode command-line tools installed. The project ships a build script that handles all the dependency management for you. Toolchains, third-party libraries, the whole pipeline. Clone the'

[03:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'repository, run the build script, and the first build takes maybe 20 to 30 minutes on modern hardware. Subsequent builds are incremental and fast. The result is a working browser binary that you can run locally, point at any'

[04:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'website, and watch render through an engine nobody at Google, Apple, or Mozilla wrote. For developers who want to contribute, the project documentation is unusually clear about what work is needed and how to get started. There\'s a'

[04:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'permanent issue list of well-scoped beginner tasks, and the maintainers actually review pull requests on a reasonable timeline. Compared to the current browser ecosystem directly, the case for Ladybird is structural rather'

[04:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'than feature-by-feature. Chromium powers Chrome, Edge, Brave, Opera, Vivaldi, Arc, and roughly every embedded browser shipped in the last 5 years, which means a single rendering engine governed by a single corporation'

[04:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is now responsible for how the majority of the web is displayed. WebKit ships on every iPhone and is governed by Apple. Gecko, Mozilla\'s engine, is increasingly underfunded and arguably in maintenance'

[04:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mode. For practical purposes, the web has been a duopoly since the mid-2010s, and the trajectory is toward monoculture. Ladybird is not going to break that trajectory in 2026, but it is the only project with a realistic shot'

[05:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'at building a fourth viable engine governed by an organization that has no commercial incentive to bend standards toward a particular business model. That is worth funding even if you never end up using the browser as your daily'

[05:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'driver. Ladybird is led by Andreas Kling, the same engineer who started SerenityOS as a hobby project after recovering from addiction roughly a decade ago. The team around him is genuinely small relative to the scope. Eight full-time'

[05:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'paid engineers, plus a community of volunteer contributors that has grown into the thousands over the project\'s lifetime. The funding model is also worth understanding because it is unusual. The project takes no venture capital, takes'

[05:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'no search engine deals, takes no advertising revenue. The entire operation is funded by recurring sponsorships from companies like Fudo, Shopify, and Cloudflare, plus individual donations through GitHub sponsors and'

[05:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the Ladybird browser initiative directly. That funding model is what gives the team the latitude to make engineering decisions on a multi-year horizon rather than against a quarterly metric. It is a structural advantage that almost no other browser team'

[06:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'currently has. If you want to actually try Ladybird, the code base compiles cleanly on modern Linux and macOS today, and the developer alpha for those platforms is targeted for 2026. Windows users can build through WSL 2 in'

[06:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the meantime. If you want to support the project without writing any code, the Ladybird browser initiative accepts donations through its website. Recurring sponsorships at any amount help materially because the funding model is'

[06:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the entire point of the project\'s independence. If you want to contribute code, the issue tracker on GitHub is genuinely well curated with beginner-friendly tasks tagged and the maintainer team that reviews pull'

[06:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'requests on a reasonable cadence. The repository is linked in the description. If this video saved you a research afternoon on the state of independent browsers, star the repository on GitHub. Visibility actually matters for a'

[06:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'nonprofit funded by sponsorships. Subscribe to Awesome Foss for more open source projects worth caring about.'
